{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646314"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:28:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:28:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18172"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18172"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10886"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79289"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10886"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18172"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64611"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7302"},{"type":"tags","id":"7314"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25316"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25319"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79289"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the number of vertebral arches in the coccyx?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["0","1","2","3","4"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe coccyx, commonly referred to as the tailbone, is composed of four fused vertebrae. These vertebrae do not have distinct vertebral arches, which are characteristic of the more superior vertebrae in the spinal column. The coccyx is a rudimentary structure that serves as an attachment site for various ligaments, tendons, and muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer as the coccyx lacks the typical vertebral arches found in other parts of the spine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003E2\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003E3\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003E4\u003C/strong\u003E are incorrect as they suggest the presence of distinct vertebral arches, which are not present in the coccyx.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The coccyx consists of four fused vertebrae and does not have distinct vertebral arches.","The coccyx serves as an attachment site for various ligaments, tendons, and muscles."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","DeSai C, Reddy V, Agarwal A. Anatomy, Back, Vertebral Column. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525969/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64611"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18172"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64611"},"attributes":{"c